}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metrics, traces, and logs so far. Metric-level anomaly scans across the five candidate services produced no sustained resource faults: only the 'error' metric (always 0) showed full-window hits for ts-auth and ts-order (not actionable). Focusing on the candidate services' traces revealed the strongest signals: traces related to ts-travel-service (trace.from_ts-travel-service.duration_mean and duration_p95, trace.to_ts-travel-service.*) showed exceedances first (earliest exceed timestamp 1705982580) and then trace.to_ts-order-service.duration_* exceeded later (earliest exceed timestamp 1705982880). This ordering implies ts-travel-service latency rose earlier and then impacted downstream calls (including to order-service). A focused metric check for ts-travel-service showed only sparse P95 breaches (2 points per KPI) across cpu, mem, socket, diskio, latency KPIs — not long consecutive faults — so there is no clear resource-level fault (CPU/memory/disk/socket) according to global-P95-based metric detection. Trace error rates are zero, so errors/failures did not spike. error_logs.csv is empty. To further localize cause (application vs network vs resource), we should inspect ts-travel-service logs inside the incident window for any messages (e.g., warnings about downstream timeouts, slow DB queries, socket errors) that explain the increased latency. Currently the strongest hypothesis is that ts-travel-service experienced service-level latency (application or network latency) starting around 1705982580 (2024-01-23 ~03:56–04:03 UTC) and that this propagated to downstream services like ts-order-service later. However, we need logs to confirm whether the reason is socket/network errors, external dependency slowness, or internal application slowness.",
